<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-06T10:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-06T10:00:00-05:00" n="113" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 PW/8–345: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-08-06T11:00:00-04:00">August 6,
                                1945—11 a.m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1204. The following telegram has been received from the Secretary in reply to
                        your No. 1279:<note n="80" xml:id="d113fn80">August 3, 11 p.m., <ref target="#pg_144">p. 144</ref>.</note>
                    </p>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“By direction of the President, please inform Chiang Kai-shek that no
                            American officers will be assigned to high command in the China Theater
                            who are objectionable to him.</p>
                        <p>General Stilwell will not be assigned to the China Theater.”</p>
                    </quote>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>